[
    {
        "content": "<p>I have a monad <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>P</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>μ</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>δ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(P,\\mu,\\delta)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03785em;\">δ</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> on a cartesian category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span></span></span> (in fact the Giry monad on the category of standard Borel spaces, which may or may not be relevant) and I have an algebra of that monad, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>ε</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(A,\\varepsilon)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ε</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>I hope to show that my algebra is free, i.e. that there exists some object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>ε</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(A,\\varepsilon)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ε</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is isomorphic to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>μ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(P(X),\\mu)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> as an algebra. However, I don't know what <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is a priori. (In fact I want to define something as the unique-up-to-iso <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> is free on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, assuming it is indeed unique.)</p>\n<p>So I'm hoping for a result along the lines of \"an algebra of a monad is free if and only if ...\", where assessing the \"...\" doesn't require finding the object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> on which it's free. If there is such a characterisation then maybe I can use it to prove that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> is free. Does anyone know of one?</p>\n<p>(<strong>edit:</strong> as usually happens after I post something publicly, I <em>think</em> I've solved my problem a different way ... <strong>edit 2:</strong> actually that didn't work, so I think I do still need this)</p>",
        "id": 496332915,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathaniel Virgo",
        "timestamp": 1738070286
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'd expect that projectivity is a necessary condition: along every surjective morphism of algebras <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B \\to C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>, it must be possible to lift every algebra morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\to C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> to an algebra morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\to B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 496344667,
        "sender_full_name": "Tobias Fritz",
        "timestamp": 1738073649
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is obviously necessary for algebras of <em>any</em> monad on Set to be free: in your notation, if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> is free then algebra morphisms out of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> are in bijection with arbitrary maps out of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, and these can be lifted by the axiom of choice. Since standard Borel measurable spaces behave set-like in many ways, I'd hope that this still applies.</p>\n<p>For some monads this projectivity condition is both necessary and sufficient for an algebra to be free, and intuitively I'd wager that the Giry monad is one of them.</p>\n<p><em>Edit:</em> Thanks to <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"318831\">@Areeb SM</span> for pointing out that what I said wasn't obvious at all (and probably not quite right). Should be fixed now.</p>",
        "id": 496344797,
        "sender_full_name": "Tobias Fritz",
        "timestamp": 1738073691
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Another necessary condition for being a free algebra is being a coalgebra for the comonad on the category of algebras induced by the free-forgetful adjunction.  If the monadic adjunction is also comonadic, then this condition is sufficient, and the object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> on which a coalgebra algebra <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> is free can be recovered as the equalizer of the coalgebra structure map and the unit of the monad.</p>",
        "id": 496395340,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1738087647
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That reminds me of another necessary condition: a free Giry algebra <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> has a \"codiagonal\" algebra morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\to A \\otimes A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>, which is basically the EM algebra version of the copy map in a Markov category. This codiagonal has the characteristic property that composing with the projection <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\to I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span> on either tensor factor gives the identity <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\to A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>. Some people call such a thing a <em>broadcasting map</em>, because it \"broadcasts\" elements of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> to both tensor factors. It need not be commutative or associative though, just counital.</p>",
        "id": 496398874,
        "sender_full_name": "Tobias Fritz",
        "timestamp": 1738088773
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The fact that not all Giry algebras have a broadcasting map is closely related to the no-cloning theorem in quantum theory. (I can go into more details if anyone wants to see them.)</p>",
        "id": 496399298,
        "sender_full_name": "Tobias Fritz",
        "timestamp": 1738088916
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Morally speaking, the <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/quant-ph/0611295\">no-broadcasting theorem for general probabilistic theories</a> says that the existence of a broadcasting map characterizes the free algebras. Technically, it's slightly different because they don't formally consider Giry algebras. But I'm fairly sure that the same result holds for Giry algebras, even if I wouldn't know how to prove it offhand.</p>",
        "id": 496399587,
        "sender_full_name": "Tobias Fritz",
        "timestamp": 1738089028
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Characterising.20free.20algebras/near/496395340\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Another necessary condition for being a free algebra is being a coalgebra for the comonad on the category of algebras induced by the free-forgetful adjunction.  If the monadic adjunction is also comonadic, then this condition is sufficient, and the object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> on which a coalgebra algebra <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> is free can be recovered as the equalizer of the coalgebra structure map and the unit of the monad.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Bart Jacobs has a paper on this topic, and how these coalgebra structures can be interpreted as bases: <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1309.0844\">https://arxiv.org/pdf/1309.0844</a></p>",
        "id": 496401712,
        "sender_full_name": "JS PL (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1738089761
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276702\">Tobias Fritz</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Characterising.20free.20algebras/near/496398874\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>That reminds me of another necessary condition: a free Giry algebra <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> has a \"codiagonal\" algebra morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\to A \\otimes A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>, which is basically the EM algebra version of the copy map in a Markov category. This codiagonal has the characteristic property that composing with the projection <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\to I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span> on either tensor factor gives the identity <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\to A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>. Some people call such a thing a <em>broadcasting map</em>, because it \"broadcasts\" elements of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> to both tensor factors. It need not be commutative or associative though, just counital.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That's curious!  Up until your last sentence I was thinking \"that must be just because the free algebra functor is strong monoidal, so it preserves comonoids, and the monoidal structure of the base category is cartesian, so every object is a comonoid\".  That's what happens in lots of other cases like vector spaces, for instance.  But if the broadcast map is not commutative or associative, it must come from somewhere else?</p>",
        "id": 496402532,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1738090051
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh for free algebras it is commutative and associative, and does come from the strong monoidal structure. I see that my phrasing with \"need not\" was confusing; I just meant that these conditions are not part of the definition of a broadcasting map!</p>",
        "id": 496408490,
        "sender_full_name": "Tobias Fritz",
        "timestamp": 1738092125
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So there seems to be the following dichotomy:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A free Giry algebra has a broadcasting map that is even associative and commutative.</li>\n<li>A non-free Giry algebra has no broadcasting map at all. (This part is conjectural, but proven in a slightly different technical setting.)</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 496408601,
        "sender_full_name": "Tobias Fritz",
        "timestamp": 1738092172
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah, I see.  So if every broadcasting map that actually exists is associative and commutative, why do people define the notion of \"broadcasting map\" that isn't associative or commutative?  (-:</p>",
        "id": 496409020,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1738092311
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Great question! I think that was based on the \"operational\" intuition by physicists that a broadcasting is a process that creates two copies of some piece of information in such a way that when you ignore or forget one, then you recover the original information. The fact that this counitality was enough for them to disprove the existence in non-free cases must have been why they didn't consider additional conditions.</p>",
        "id": 496409408,
        "sender_full_name": "Tobias Fritz",
        "timestamp": 1738092439
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here's another thing that might help: given a free algebra <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">PX</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">PX</span></span></span></span>, the image of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>η</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>P</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\eta:X\\to PX</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">η</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">PX</span></span></span></span> (for a <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/sober+measurable+space\">convenient choice</a> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>) can be taken to be the set of extreme points of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">PX</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">PX</span></span></span></span>. Those are exactly the points <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>P</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p\\in PX</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7335em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">PX</span></span></span></span> such that if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>μ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>π</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p=\\mu(\\pi)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> for some <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>π</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>P</mi><mi>P</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\pi\\in PPX</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">PPX</span></span></span></span>, then necessarily <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>π</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>η</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>p</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\pi=\\eta(p)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">η</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>(There are <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/zero-one+measure\">a few other characterizations</a>, but the one above is the one more readily generalizable outside the free case.)</p>\n<p>Now let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>e</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(A,e)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> be an algebra and let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>A</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\" lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">′</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A&#x27;</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">′</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> be the set of its extreme points (same definition as above, but with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">e</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span></span></span></span> in place of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mu</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span></span></span></span>), with the induced sigma-algebra. <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> is free if and only if any of the following equivalent conditions hold:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>Every point of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> is a unique <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/convex+mixture\">convex mixture</a> of extreme points (i.e. of a probability measure supported on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>A</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\" lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">′</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A&#x27;</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">′</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>)</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>The usual universal property holds: there's a bijection <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msup><mi>A</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\" lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">′</mo></msup><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≅</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Meas}(A&#x27;, B)\\cong\\mathrm{Alg}(A,B)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0019em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Meas</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">′</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">Alg</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, natural in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span>, given in the left direction by precomposition with the inclusion. </p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>(There are other equivalent conditions.)</p>",
        "id": 496942764,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1738308216
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(The idea of \"extreme points\" is specific to the Giry monad, and of a few other probability monads, it does not hold in general. It may be related to the <a href=\"http://www.tac.mta.ca/tac/volumes/26/22/26-22abs.html\">explicit basis property</a>.)</p>",
        "id": 496948433,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1738310782
    }
]